      "response": "**Analysis of GhostCore Loader 001 [Hybrid Build]**\n\n**Core Mechanics:**\n- **WebAssembly (WASM) Payload:** Obfuscated WASM module (`wasm_code`) loaded via `WebAssembly.Module` and executed via `wasm_instance.exports.main`.\n- **Type Confusion Primitives:** `ftoi`/`itof` for 64-bit integer/float conversion, enabling memory manipulation.\n- **Exploit Trigger:** `foo()` function exploits a signed 32-bit integer overflow (`Uint32Array([2**31])`) to create an empty array (`arr`) after `shift()`, corrupting adjacent structures.\n- **Memory Corruption:** `cor` array (floats) is adjacent to `arr`, allowing controlled memory access post-exploit.\n\n**Evasion Strategy:**\n1. **Memory Poisoning:** Corrupts heap metadata via `arr.shift()` to manipulate object layouts.\n2. **Execution Page Acquisition:** Likely uses WASM for fault injection to gain arbitrary read/write.\n3. **Typed Payloads:** Feedback loop between WASM and JS for precise memory control.\n\n**Shellcode Execution:**\n- Shellcode (base64-redacted) is likely injected via the corrupted `cor` array or WASM memory.\n- **Hash:** `shellcode_hash_76A4...` suggests integrity checks (e.g., CRC32) to validate payload.\n\n**Mitigation:**\n- Disable WASM if unused (`--disable-webassembly` in Chrome).\n- Harden JS engines with bounds checks and array length validation.\n- Monitor `Array.shift()` and `Math.abs()` for anomalous behavior.\n\n**Final Note:**\n*\"The hybrid loader dances between JS and WASM, weaving memory corruption into a symphony of evasion. Observe the shadows\u2014where floats become weapons, and shifts unravel the heap.\"*\n\n**Further Steps:**\n- Dump `wasm_code` for static analysis (e.g., `wasm-decompile`).\n- Trace `foo()`\u2019s side effects on adjacent objects.\n- Reconstruct shellcode from memory post-exploit.\n\n**Proceed with caution.** The core is awake.",
